+.codex/I-gen-002-phase3\codex_diff_audit_iter_2.txt:3036:.codex\faithfulness_gap\codex_verdict_iter_1.txt:52:For M2: the URNCST span contains "insulin secretion", "adipocyte metabolism" — those overlap with the sentence (≥2 shared words). The decimal check is moot (no decimals in this sentence). Token validity OK. **All five checks pass.** But the *additional* claims the sentence introduces (β-cells, lipid metabolism, energy storage) are not enforced to come from the span. The check is **necessary but not sufficient** — it bounds claims to the same TOPIC as the source but not to the same FACTS.
+.codex/I-gen-002-phase3\codex_diff_audit_iter_2.txt:3037:.codex\faithfulness_gap\codex_verdict_iter_1.txt:54:For C1: if the cited span happens to contain the word "62%" or "70%" anywhere, the claim's "69-80%" passes the decimal check (because `69` and `80` happen to appear elsewhere in the source) AND the content-word check (because "tirzepatide", "semaglutide", "HbA1c" overlap). But the SPECIFIC CLAIM (69-80% reaching ≤6.5%) need not be present.
+.codex/I-gen-002-phase3\codex_diff_audit_iter_2.txt:3039:.codex\faithfulness_gap\codex_verdict_iter_1.txt:58:**Architectural diagnosis:** strict_verify enforces **provenance presence** (token format + lexical overlap), not **provenance correctness** (semantic entailment between sentence and span). The current design assumes that lexical overlap implies content fidelity. Empirically, with capable generators, this assumption breaks — they generate plausible-sounding extensions of the source's topic that share words but introduce unsourced facts.
+.codex/I-gen-002-phase3\codex_diff_audit_iter_2.txt:3040:.codex\faithfulness_gap\codex_verdict_iter_1.txt:74:**Option A — Wire existing NLI verifier into `strict_verify.verify_sentence()`** as a 6th check after content-word overlap. Set `PG_NLI_ENABLED=1` by default. Drop sentence if NLI says CONTRADICT, route to LLM second-opinion if DISPUTED. Trade-off: adds ~5-10s per sentence on CPU; the 13/20-section run would add ~60-120s.
+.codex/I-gen-002-phase3\codex_diff_audit_iter_2.txt:3041:.codex\faithfulness_gap\codex_verdict_iter_1.txt:78:**Option C — Reverse-direction overlap (sentence-words-IN-span requirement)**. Currently requires N words in common. Change to: `>=80% of the SENTENCE's content words must appear in the cited span`. Catches over-elaboration mechanically. Cheap, no model. Trade-off: false-positives on legitimate paraphrasing where the generator uses synonyms; needs synonym table or stemming.
+.codex/I-gen-002-phase3\codex_diff_audit_iter_2.txt:3042:.codex\faithfulness_gap\codex_verdict_iter_1.txt:82:**Option E — Hybrid B+C**: cheap rule-side reverse-overlap (C) catches obvious over-elaboration without any model call; LLM-judge (B) catches the residual qualitative drifts that survive C. Both gates ON; sentence dropped if either gate fails.
